REST API and Idempotency
Interviewers often ask:
"Which HTTP methods are idempotent?"

GET
GET /users/100
Read operation.
Run 1000 times.
Same data returned.
Idempotent


PUT
PUT /users/100

Name = Satish
Run 100 times.
Final value remains:
Name = Satish
Idempotent


DELETE
DELETE /users/100
First call:
User deleted
Second call:
Already deleted
Final state remains deleted.
dempotent


POST
POST /users
Every call creates new record.
User 1
User 2
User 3
Not Idempotent by default

However:
POST + Idempotency Key can become idempotent.


Interview Scenario
Interviewer: Design a payment system like Stripe.
Answer:
Payments must be idempotent because network failures and retries can create duplicate transactions. Every payment request should contain an Idempotency Key. The server stores the key in a database or distributed cache. If the same key arrives again, the previously stored response is returned instead of processing the payment again." This answer immediately demonstrates distributed systems knowledge.


Idempotency in Kafka
Suppose a consumer reads:

Order Created
Consumer crashes.
Kafka sends message again.
Without idempotency:

Inventory reduced twice.
Bad.

With idempotency: Store processed event id.

EVENT-1001
When same event arrives:

Already processed
Ignore.
This is called: Exactly-Once Processing Strategy (business-level exactly once).


